8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1072, L.D. 1618, “Resolve, to Study the
10 Feasibility of Establishing a Dedicated Family Court in Maine”
11 Amend the resolve by striking out all of section 2 and inserting the following:
12 'Sec. 2. Study group membership. Resolved: That, notwithstanding Joint Rule
13 353, the study group consists of 13 members appointed as follows:
14 1. Two members of the Senate, appointed by the President of the Senate, including
15 one member from each of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats in the
16 Legislature;
17 2. Two members of the House of Representatives, appointed by the Speaker of the
18 House, including one member from each of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats
19 in the Legislature;
20 3. Three members representing the judicial branch, appointed by the Chief Justice of
21 the Supreme Judicial Court;
22 4. One member representing a child welfare advocacy organization, appointed by the
23 President of the Senate;
24 5. One member who is a guardian ad litem, appointed by the President of the Senate;
25 6. One member who is an individual with personal experience with family law
26 proceedings in court, appointed by the President of the Senate;
27 7. One member representing the Family Law Advisory Commission under the Maine
28 Revised Statutes, Title 19-A, chapter 5, appointed by the Speaker of the House;
29 8. One member representing a statewide coalition of domestic violence projects,
30 appointed by the Speaker of the House; and
31 9. One member who is an individual with personal experience with family law
32 proceedings in court, appointed by the Speaker of the House.'
33 Amend the resolve by striking out all of section 5 and inserting the following:
Page 1 - 132LR1804(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1072, L.D. 1618
1 'Sec. 5. Duties. Resolved: That the study group shall comprehensively evaluate
2 the feasibility, potential benefits and challenges associated with establishing a dedicated
3 family court system, which must include examination and consideration of:
4 1. Best practices in other states with dedicated family courts;
5 2. How best to structure a dedicated family court to ensure that it is available and
6 accessible to parties across all areas of the State, including rural areas. The study group
7 shall consider whether specific judges, mediators and other court staff should be assigned
8 to work exclusively on family matters cases and whether to require single-judge
9 assignments for specific cases or specific families;
10 3. What categories of legal proceedings should be within the exclusive jurisdiction of
11 a dedicated family court, such as all divorce, legal separation and annulment proceedings
12 or only those proceedings involving minor children; paternity, parental rights and
13 responsibilities and child support proceedings; some or all protection from abuse
14 proceedings; child protection proceedings; and some or all guardianship, adoption and
15 related proceedings under the Maine Uniform Probate Code;
16 4. Data on the volume of cases within the different categories identified in subsection
17 3 currently handled by the State’s courts, the number of times individual cases are heard
18 by multiple judges, the average time to resolution for these categories of cases and the
19 potential for reducing delays and improving outcomes in these categories of cases through
20 a dedicated family court; and
21 5. The resources required to establish a dedicated family court system.
22 In performing its duties under this section, the study group shall solicit the input, advice
23 or participation of the Department of Health and Human Services, Office of Child and
24 Family Services and the Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Support
25 Enforcement and Recovery, attorneys within the Office of the Attorney General with
26 experience in child protection proceedings and restorative justice professionals.'
27 Amend the resolve by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
28 section number to read consecutively.
29 SUMMARY
3300 This amendment requires that the legislative members of the Study Group to Research
3311 the Feasibility of Establishing a Dedicated Family Court in Maine, as established in the
3322 resolve, include members from each of the 2 parties holding the largest number of seats in
3333 the Legislature. It also provides that the Chief Justice of the Supreme Judicial Court
3344 appoints the 3 representatives of the judicial branch who serve as members of the study
3355 group. Finally, it provides more specificity regarding the duties of the study group and
3366 directs that, when performing those duties, the study group must solicit the input, advice or
3377 participation of the Department of Health and Human Services, Office of Child and Family
3388 Services and the Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Support
3399 Enforcement and Recovery, attorneys within the Office of the Attorney General with
4400 experience in child protection proceedings and restorative justice professionals.
4411 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
